Package: multpois
Title: Analyze Nominal Responses via the Multinomial-Poisson Trick
Version: 0.0.0.9200
Authors@R: 
    person("Jacob O.", "Wobbrock", , "wobbrock@uw.edu", role = c("aut", "cre"),
           comment = c(ORCID = "0000-0003-3675-5491"))
Maintainer: Jacob O. Wobbrock <wobbrock@uw.edu>
Description: Dichotomous responses with two categories can be analyzed
    with 'glm' or 'lme4::glmer' using the 'family=binomial' option.
    Unfortunately, polytomous responses with three or more unordered
    categories cannot be analyzed similarly because there is no
    'family=multinomial' option. For between-subjects data,
    'nnet::multinom' addresses this need, but it cannot handle random
    factors and therefore cannot handle repeated measures. To address this
    issue, this package implements the multinomial-Poisson trick (Baker
    1994, Chen & Kuo 2001, Guimaraes 2004, Lee et al. 2017), which
    transforms nominal response data into counts for each categorical
    alternative. These counts are then analyzed using 'glm' with
    'family=poisson' for between-subjects data, or 'lme4::glmer' with
    'family=poisson' for within-subjects data.  Omnibus analysis of
    variance results can be obtained along with post hoc pairwise
    comparisons.
